    # [Scene: City Hall — Council Atrium | Morning]

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain on the glass roof like a persistent metronome. Voices fold and refold — argument, reassurance, the ratcheting click of camera shutters.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fast, bright strings underscored by a low, driving percussion — insistence, momentum.]
    "The memorandum you refused the night before sits on a folding table in the middle of the atrium like an accusation and a promise at once. People cluster around it — neighbors in patched jackets, a"
    "few reporters, lawyers moving with careful, professional agitation. The council clerk announces a delay: procedural review, legal filings, 'further consultation.' The words taste like a bruise — sharp but not fatal."
    "You feel the adrenaline like heat in your palms. This is not the smooth victory you wanted. It's a bruise you can work through. It will hurt. It will force you to move faster, to be smarter, to trust more."
    "Irene Voss stands with her shoulders steady, an unreadable expression sculpted into professional countenance. She watches you as if cataloguing weather patterns rather than people. Luca circles behind her like a bright brochure folded into human form, smiling toward cameras with a patience that is practiced and exact."
    "Sami finds you first, a wick of nervous energy and furious tenderness all at once."
    show sami_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    sami_alvarez "They tabled it. Legal's got their teeth in it. People are pissed — and relieved. Strange combo."
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "Relieved because we didn't sell out. Pissed because the clock doesn't care for legal wrangling."

    sami_alvarez "Clock's exactly why we don't trust their timeline. We move while they argue."

    maya_rios "You and your kayaks. What's the first move?"

    sami_alvarez "Micro-pilots tonight. Boardwalk, three terraces, the Spire. We split teams. We take what we can build without permits and call it 'emergency repairs.'"
    "Your throat closes and opens in the same breath. Relief is buoyant and sharp: you did not sign away community veto. The council's delay is a bruise — but bruises seed new muscle. The decision to"
    "refuse has taken the brittle single spine of a city plan and started to braid it into a rope."
    "Dr. Noor arrives with a stack of annotated maps pressed to her chest like scriptures. She's quiet on the surface, riven with that scientist's grief-joy: data that terrifies, clarity that propels."
    show dr_noor_patel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_noor_patel "Legal delays are expected. The injunction requests buy time for cover-ups. But they also make space — space for distributed action. If you lead federated coordination, the city's delay becomes our advantage."

    maya_rios "Lead… the coordination?"

    dr_noor_patel "You know the neighborhoods, you know the hydrology, and people listen when you speak. You were already building trust while they polished renderings. This is your momentum."
    "Your pulse spikes — not panic but electric clarity. The path forks again, but the stakes are different now. It isn't bureaucratic negotiation; it's organizing the city into a thousand hands that will stitch the shoreline from the inside."
    hide sami_alvarez
    hide maya_rios
    hide dr_noor_patel

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # [Scene: Harborfront District — Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Hammer strikes, laughter, the slap of nylon against wood, a child's shout muffled across the water.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive, kinetic rhythms — upbeat, vigorous; brass accents signal small triumphs.]
    "You move like a node in a feverish network: gelting plans into calls, redirecting volunteer teams, patching a momentary dispute between two neighbors about whether to move a donated pallet. Every instruction you give is quick, practical; every pause opens for someone to say a thing only they are holding."

    "Neighbor A" "If we stack the pallets here and anchor with the old pilings, it'll slow the surge at that angle."

    "Neighbor B" "But the runoff will pool back toward my door."
    show maya_rios at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "Then we put a siphon there and plant the berm with dune grass to filter and slow. Sami's team can run a temporary pump until roots take hold."
    "You touch wet rope with callused fingers, the smell of kelp and oil and warm coffee. Your solar pendant flashes once as you bend to tie a knot your brother taught you the year before the"
    "big storm — the same hands that learned to hold through a losing world now hold this stubborn, hopeful building."

    menu:
        "Kneel and help anchor the pallet.":
            "You crouch, palms muddy and sure. The knot holds; a neighbor claps your shoulder."
        "Walk the line, coordinate teams.":
            "You step back and shout directions, voice cutting through the bustle. Teams fall into sync like migrating birds."

    # --- merge ---
    "The micro-choice reframes the tempo but not the outcome. Whether you are elbow-deep or coordinating, the harborfront heals in small, iterative fixes."
    "The micro-choice reframes the tempo but not the outcome. Whether you are elbow-deep or coordinating, the harborfront heals in small, iterative fixes. The arousal hums higher: every successful anchor is a small drumbeat toward something larger."
    # [Scene: The Green Spire — Dusk / Federated Sites Montage]
    hide maya_rios

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A mosaic of voices — instruction, questions, laughter, a radio playing a hopeful song. Night insects join the symphony.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rapid building string ostinato with triumphant horns; tempo pushes, breathes, accelerates.]
    "Elliot Chen is everywhere — his hands flourished with dirt and blueprints. He moves from table to table, eyes bright, teaching how to weave living-mattes, how to seed dunegrass, how to splice reclaimed rebar into clever,"
    "resilient frames. When he sees you, his smile is the kind you remember from the first wet prototype run — equal parts mischief and faith."
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "You scared to let go?"
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "Not scared — practical. People died when commitments were half-made. That's why we held firm."

    elliot_chen "And yet here you are, holding more hands than documents."

    maya_rios "Because hands build faster than signatures when the tide is coming."
    "He reaches for a coil of rope and hands it to you the way someone hands a coin to a friend for safekeeping. The contact is small and electric, an everyday vow. His optimism is contagious and tethering. He speaks fast, practical, tender."

    elliot_chen "I'll run training circuits. Weekends, weeknights — I can bring teams to the Outer Blocks, the Boardwalk, the Dune. We make sure every crew knows what to do when water rises."

    maya_rios "You sure you want to do that? It's… a big ask."

    elliot_chen "Big asks are for big stakes. And—' [Falters, then steadies] '—I want to be here for it. For you. For the work."
    "The confession isn't cinematic; it's earnest and small, a line delivered between a smear of paint and a bolt. You answer with a look that says trust is the next structure you both will have to engineer."
    "Later that night, you draft a resignation notice — not a dramatic rip, but a practical, precise handover. You do it in a quiet corner of the Spire while hammering continues below, while volunteers debate the best grain for sandbags."
    show dr_noor_patel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_noor_patel "You could keep the title and leverage municipal resources while you build the federation."

    maya_rios "I could, but there's a power calculus that changes the trust equation. If I sit at that table, people will see me as city first, neighbor second. I want neighbors first."

    dr_noor_patel "Sacrifice is heavy, but sometimes it rearranges the world."
    "Your resignation is a rearrangement. Giving up a seat on a municipal bench is a bruise and a kind of freedom. It pulls you out of bureaucratic compromise and into a nimble, decentralized network that can be ruthless in its speed."

    menu:
        "Send the resignation email now.":
            "You hit send with a hand that doesn't tremble. A thousand small messages ripple across your phone; volunteers cheer downstairs."
        "Save the draft and go help Elliot.":
            "You tuck the device away and lift a hammer. Elliot laughs and calls you a coward in the best way; you laugh back and build until the sky goes dark."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both choices are honest; both move the work forward."
    "Both choices are honest; both move the work forward. The arousal crescendos through the night: workshops, whispered strategy sessions across alleyways, legal aid clinics setting up tables in church basements. The energy is relentless and, crucially, shared."
